Read in Aggression data

# Aggression data
dat<-read.csv("~/Desktop/Bachelorarbeit/AggressionResults.csv",sep=";")

#modifiying data
dat<-tidyr::separate(dat,Combination,c("Intruder","Recipient"),sep=" *- *")
dat$IntruderPop<-as.factor(gsub("([A-z]+?)\\ .*","\\1", dat$Intruder))
dat$Recipient<-as.factor(gsub("\\s","",dat$Recipient,perl=T)) # remove whitespaces

#change Recipients
dat$RecipientCol<-as.factor(gsub(" ","",dat$Recipient)) # remove spaces
levels(dat$RecipientCol)[levels(dat$RecipientCol)=="A"]<-"Una080"
levels(dat$RecipientCol)[levels(dat$RecipientCol)=="B"]<-"Una054"
levels(dat$RecipientCol)[levels(dat$RecipientCol)=="C"]<-"Ita014"
levels(dat$RecipientCol)[levels(dat$RecipientCol)=="D"]<-"Ita025"
levels(dat$RecipientCol)[levels(dat$RecipientCol)=="E"]<-"Ita013"
levels(dat$RecipientCol)[levels(dat$RecipientCol)=="F"]<-"Una081"
levels(dat$RecipientCol)[levels(dat$RecipientCol)=="G"]<-"Ita024"
levels(dat$RecipientCol)[levels(dat$RecipientCol)=="H"]<-"Una082"
levels(dat$RecipientCol)[levels(dat$RecipientCol)=="I"]<-"Una007"
levels(dat$RecipientCol)[levels(dat$RecipientCol)=="J"]<-"Ita015"

dat$RecipientPop<-as.factor(gsub(" ","",dat$Recipient)) # remove spaces
levels(dat$RecipientPop)[levels(dat$RecipientPop)=="A"]<-"Una"
levels(dat$RecipientPop)[levels(dat$RecipientPop)=="B"]<-"Una"
levels(dat$RecipientPop)[levels(dat$RecipientPop)=="C"]<-"Ita"
levels(dat$RecipientPop)[levels(dat$RecipientPop)=="D"]<-"Ita"
levels(dat$RecipientPop)[levels(dat$RecipientPop)=="E"]<-"Ita"
levels(dat$RecipientPop)[levels(dat$RecipientPop)=="F"]<-"Una"
levels(dat$RecipientPop)[levels(dat$RecipientPop)=="G"]<-"Ita"
levels(dat$RecipientPop)[levels(dat$RecipientPop)=="H"]<-"Una"
levels(dat$RecipientPop)[levels(dat$RecipientPop)=="I"]<-"Una"
levels(dat$RecipientPop)[levels(dat$RecipientPop)=="J"]<-"Ita"

#add combination of Una+Ita
dat$comb<-paste(dat$IntruderPop,dat$RecipientPop,sep="-")

# chemical data
chcdat<-read.csv("~/Desktop/Bachelorarbeit/Cardio_CHC_prepdata.csv",sep=";",dec=",")

#used libraries
library(ggbiplot)

# get rid of NAs for CHC dataframe

#standardization with internal C12-STD
chcdatng1   <- chcdat[,11:98] / chcdat[,10]

#relative responses 
chcdatng    <- chcdat[,11:98] / sum(chcdat[,11:89])

#combine nanogram amounts and sample information from chcdat
chcdatng<-cbind(chcdat[,1:9],chcdatng)


## splitting up the data  

# all queen-colonies for PCA
allchcdat1<-subset(chcdatng, Caste == "queen ")
allchcdat<-subset(allchcdat1[-c(22:24), ])

# only queen and worker (BR) for PCA
workerdata<-subset(chcdatng, Caste %in% c("queen ","worker"))
workerdat1<-subset(workerdata[-c(11:24), ])
workerdat<-subset(workerdat1[-c(18) ])

# manipulated and untreated queens PCA
washdata<-subset(chcdatng, Caste %in% c("dead queen"))
washdat<-subset(washdata[-c(4,6:9,18,25,42)])

Logistic regression analysis

## check out https://www.r-bloggers.com/how-to-perform-ordinal-logistic-regression-in-r/
# https://stackoverflow.com/questions/33316686/r-plotting-predictions-of-mass-polr-ordinal-model
# https://stats.stackexchange.com/questions/89474/interpretation-of-ordinal-logistic-regression

library(MASS)
agg<-as.factor(fulldata$Aggression)
CHCdistance<-fulldata$CHCdist

# simplify Queens vector a bit
queens<-as.factor(gsub(".queens","",as.character(fulldata$Queens),perl=T))

m<-(polr(agg~CHCdistance*queens))

summary(m)

Interpretation of ordinal regression

ctable
##                                Value Std. Error t value     p sign
## CHCdistance                    0.053      0.071   0.746 0.456     
## queensmanipulated              -3.96      1.325  -2.988 0.003    *
## queensuntreated               -1.136       0.97  -1.171 0.242     
## CHCdistance:queensmanipulated -0.042      0.137  -0.307 0.759     
## CHCdistance:queensuntreated    0.049      0.101   0.482  0.63     
## 1|2                           -1.969      0.737   -2.67 0.008    *
## 2|3                           -0.167      0.677  -0.246 0.806     
## 3|4                            0.171      0.681   0.251 0.802     
## 4|5                            2.573      0.807    3.19 0.001    *

This shows the results of the modelling analysis.

In the first row, the Value column in the dis row shows that with increasing distance, there is an increase in the aggressive response (increasing distance by 1 increases aggression by 0.0105).

The table shows how aggressive the ants were relative to the aggression against living queens. So, we can see in the quunwashed queens row that untreated queens received significantly (the sign column) less (the Value is negative) aggression than living queens. Similarly, manipulated queens received significantly less aggression.

This can all be visualized in a very handsome plot:

plot(allEffects(m),ylab="Probability",xlab="CHC distance",  type="probability",style="stacked",colors=colorRampPalette(c("white","steelblue"))(9))
## 
## Re-fitting to get Hessian

This plot now shows how the probability of the aggression for various conditions. As you can see the probability to get aggression = 1 in the mqnipulated queens is very high, regardless of the distance between the colonies. For living and untreated, you can see that the probability to score something other than aggression=1 increases with distance.
